<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-951-124  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 951 124.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Wall Street Journal  Dec 11 1989 pA7A(N) pA7A(L) 14 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>U.S. considers easing export restraints on technological gear tothe East bloc. (telecommunications equipment, computers and othervaluable products)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lachica, Eduardo.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US government is considering easing restrictions on exports ofcomputers, telecommunications equipment and other importantproducts to Eastern Europe, benefitting Hungary, Poland and otherEastern countries, but not the Soviet Union.andP;  The initiative wasmotivated by requests from Poland, Hungary and Czechoslovakia foreasier access to Western technology.andP;  Pressures from West Europeanallies has also prompted the US to relax technological exportrules.andP;  The Department of Commerce may consider exports on acase-by-case basis, allowing specific shipments to enter, butexcluding others.andP;  Each Eastern country would make arrangementswith Western suppliers for preventing goods from being used inunauthorized ways.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Department of CommerceTelecommunicationsEastern EuropeExportRestraint of TradeComputers.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>